    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="193"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d193">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins Papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Minister of Supply</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Beaverbrook</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the President’s Special Assistant</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-29">December 29,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Harry</hi>, I spent the afternoon in the
                    Vice-President’s office.<note n="1" xml:id="d193fn1">See the memorandum of
                        conversation by Nelson, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_136"
                            >p. 136</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The conference went very well, I thought. The sights were raised immensely, but
                    not nearly high enough.</p>
                <p>At 35,000 tanks, the programme is far from meeting the necessities of the United
                    States and Bussia.</p>
                <p>On the aircraft programme, I fear the meeting was somewhat confused and
                    indecisive.</p>
                <p>Lovett put forward his estimates in gross totals which included trainers.</p>
                <p>He stated his production to the middle months of 1943. The discussion did not get
                    back to the operational requirements of 1942.</p>
                <p>Now I have been 18 months on the job of stirring men up to do more
                    production.</p>
                <p>If Britain had not taken the task seriously in the summer of 1940, the war would
                    have been ended.</p>
                <p>France fell for the want of adequate supplies of tanks and aircraft.</p>
                <p>America cannot stand on the programmes of 1942.</p>
                <p>Is there anything more I can do?</p>
                <p>Yours ever,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Max</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
